response:
Certainly! Below is the Terraform configuration for an egress-only internet gateway in AWS. You'll need to ensure you have defined a VPC here and that you're referring to it correctly; adjust the `vpc_id` as needed. The tagged internet gateway will use the `permissions` tag.

```hcl
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-west-2" # Replace this with your AWS region
}

resource "aws_vpc" "main" {
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16" # Replace this with your VPC's CIDR block
}

resource "aws_internet_gateway" "pike" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id
  tags = {
    Name = "Pike"
    permissions = "egress-only"
  }
}

resource "aws_main_route_table_association" "main" {
  main_route_table_id = aws_vpc.main.main_route_table_id
  vpc_id            = aws_vpc.main.id

  route {
    gateway_id = aws_internet_gateway.pike.id
    destination_cidr_block = "0.0.0.0/0" # Allow egress for IPv6
    }
}
```

This configuration assumes the availability of only one route table per VPC. Adjust the VPC and region specifications to your needs. The `aws_main_route_table_association` resource only includes egress traffic routes, to ensure no inbound traffic is allowed.

